*Approach 1 — CORS configured in the YAML composition

  CORS rules can be placed directly in the endpoint YAML file under a top-level <<<composition: cors:>>>
  key.  All fields of {{{/apidocs/net/officefloor/spring/starter/rest/cors/ComposeCorsConfiguration.html}ComposeCorsConfiguration}}
  are available: <<<allowed-origins>>>, <<<allowed-origin-patterns>>>, <<<allowed-methods>>>,
  <<<allowed-headers>>>, <<<exposed-headers>>>, <<<allow-credentials>>>, <<<allow-private-network>>>,
  and <<<max-age>>>.

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/composition.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The service class itself has no CORS knowledge — it just responds:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/CompositionCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 2 — <<<@CrossOrigin>>> annotation on the service class

  Spring's standard <<<@CrossOrigin>>> annotation placed on the service class is discovered by
  OfficeFloor at startup.  It walks the composition graph of each endpoint and collects every
  <<<@CrossOrigin>>> it finds, merging the results.

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/AnnotationCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The YAML file needs no CORS configuration — the annotation is enough:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/annotation.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 3 — All HTTP methods covered by a method-less YAML file

  A YAML file <<without>> an HTTP method suffix (e.g. <<<all-methods.yml>>> rather than
  <<<all-methods.GET.yml>>>) acts as a shared composition that applies to every HTTP method
  exposed by that endpoint.  Place CORS directly under the top-level <<<cors:>>> key:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/all-methods.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  Each per-method YAML file then only needs to declare its service class:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/all-methods.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/AllMethodsCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 4 — Global CORS via <<<WebMvcConfigurer>>>

  Spring's standard <<<WebMvcConfigurer.addCorsMappings()>>> mechanism works transparently with
  OfficeFloor-managed endpoints.  Register a <<<@Configuration>>> class that implements
  <<<WebMvcConfigurer>>> and map the URL patterns that should be covered:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/CorsMvcWebConfigurerConfig.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  The endpoint YAML files need no CORS configuration — they only declare the service class:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/mvc-configurer/origin.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/GlobalCorsService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Approach 5 — Global CORS via <<<CorsConfigurationSource>>> bean

  A <<<CorsConfigurationSource>>> bean gives full programmatic control over CORS rules and is
  consumed by Spring Security's <<<CorsFilter>>> when Spring Security is on the classpath.
  For OfficeFloor-managed endpoints, mirror the same rules via <<<addCorsMappings()>>> so that
  Spring MVC's CORS machinery also picks them up:

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestcors/CorsConfigurationSourceConfig.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  Again, the endpoint YAML files only declare the service class:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/cors/cors-config-source/origin.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Testing

  Tests send an <<<Origin>>> header.  When the origin is on the allow-list the response carries
  <<<Access-Control-Allow-Origin>>>.  When it is not, Spring returns <<<403 Forbidden>>> and the
  header is absent:

